          "notes": [
            {
              "title": "'Om … te' infinitive construction",
              "body": "'Om … te + infinitive' expresses purpose or sufficiency: 'genoeg om … op te eten' = 'enough to eat'. The separable prefix 'op' from 'opeten' (to eat up) moves to just before 'te'."
            },
            {
              "title": "'Is het niet?' as a tag question",
              "body": "'Is het niet?' (literally 'is it not?') is a Dutch tag question like 'isn't it?' / 'right?' in English. It is invariable — it doesn't change to match the subject."
            },
            {
              "title": "'Lekker' — versatile word",
              "body": "'Lekker' primarily means 'tasty/delicious' for food, but is broadly used as 'nicely / pleasantly'. Here it colors 'eten' (eating) positively."
            },
            {
              "title": "Present tense for future plans",
              "body": "'De kat komt niet op zolder' and 'wij gaan niet' use present tense to state facts/plans — Dutch frequently uses present tense where English might use future."
            }
          ]
